**Methodologies:**
- **Materials:** The study involved "Internet jokes" extracted from Facebook pages with entertaining content, categorized into Covid Verbal, Covid Meme, and Covid Strip (each with varying themes from innocuous to dark) and non-Covid Verbal, which served as a baseline.
- **Personality Assessment:** Two scales were used: the Coping Humor Scale (CHS) and the Life Orientation Test – Revised (LOTR) to measure humor use in stress coping and dispositional optimism.
- **Psychological Distance:** Three forms were assessed — perceived risk of infection (1-10 scale), spatial distance from the epicenter of the outbreak, and social distance based on known Covid-19 cases among acquaintances.
- **Participants:** 1751 native Italian speakers participated, recruited through social media and other channels, with complete demographics collected.
- **Procedure:** A web-based survey was conducted via LimeSurvey® with participants rating humor items for funniness and aversiveness on 7-point scales.

**Results:**
- Covid-19 humor was found to be more aversive than non-pandemic humor.
- Individuals who used humor to cope with stress found Covid-19 humor funnier and less aversive.
- Higher perceived risk of SARS-CoV-2 infection increased Covid-19 humor aversiveness.
- Greater spatial distance from the contagion epicenter allowed participants to enjoy all types of humor more.

**Conclusions:**
